    # [Scene: Rooftop Common Garden | Morning]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, ascending piano motif; soft wind chimes layered beneath]
    "You keep your palms open to the light, feeling the damp warmth that morning sun steals from the mist. The rooftop smells of wet soil and citrus from a volunteer's pot of lemon balm; insects hum like a stitched-together metronome. Underfoot, repurposed decking creaks with a familiar, kindly protest."
    "This is where the choice you made in the hall first gets a shape: not a policy memo or a press photo, but a tray of seedlings you can hand to a neighbor and a layout"
    "of wicking beds taped in permanent marker. The plan is small and stubbornly practical—pilot plots, shared tools, training that teaches people to build resilience with their own hands. It fits you."
    show arin_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "They're holding. I didn't think the graft would take so fast."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "It helped that you watered them on the night watch."

    arin_voss "We both watered. Besides, Etta swore she'd haunt me if I let the plugs die."
    "He leans back on his heels and offers you a trowel without waiting for you to ask. The motion is small, ordinary; the invitation is quieter than his grin but deeper."
    "You take the trowel. The metal is cool; the handle smells faintly of salt and tobacco from someone before him. You press into the soil and feel it give in a way that promises root."

    arin_voss "How are you holding up with all the meetings? You looked half-buried in paper yesterday."

    mira_solace "Better than the sea-floor, but less dramatic. The pilots feel... tangible. I like tangible."

    arin_voss "Tangible's good. It keeps the lawyers off our necks for a bit."
    "You both laugh, the sound soft between the plants. Conversation tumbles into logistics and practical jokes—what will be the first street to try water-resistant thresholds, who has an extra tarp, which kid has a better knot than you—but beneath it all is the same current: people are showing up."

    menu:
        "Map the first pilot beds with Arin":
            "You kneel beside him and start sketching a layout, the two of you passing ideas like seeds—spacing for tide, a shallow berm here, a shared compost pit there. Arin's fingers point at places you hadn't thought of, and each new line on the paper feels like a small agreement."
        "Talk community outreach with Etta's notes":
            "You take Etta's folded pages and read aloud. The language is old and precise: keep the meetings small, take notes, give everyone a turn. You and Arin practice inviting phrasing; the exercise steadies you both, and you leave with a rehearsed script that feels gentler than a poster."

    # --- merge ---
    "The rooftop hums with small decisions made aloud and quietly recorded. You tuck a folded list into your notebook—a roster, a materials run, a date pegged to the low tide. The seed trays are heavier than"
    "you expect when you lift them, and you feel their weight like a promise you have to carry."
    # [Scene: Old Pier Neighborhood | Late Morning]
    hide arin_voss
    hide mira_solace

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls, the slap of dock lines against pilings, a rhythmic hammering from a repair team]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Layered strings with a hopeful rising motif]
    "The Old Pier smells of brine and citrus and a hundred dinners. People pass you a bowl of thick stew; someone ties a bright ribbon to a post. This is the community you grew up in—patched,"
    "stubborn, alive—and the pilot work you chose is meant to be alive in the same way."
    show etta_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_maren "We start with what people already do. Bump up door sills, stack sand boxes where the low patch is, save seeds in a dry tin. Teach one mother how to make a raised bed and four will follow."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "That's the plan. Small anchors people can build from their porches."

    etta_maren "Anchors make people remember how to hold."
    "Noah appears, sleeves rolled, carrying a coil of treated rope and a bundle of salvaged plywood. He hasn't been lost to the strain of recent months, but the lines around his mouth are deeper; his shop is a headline you keep in the back of your head."
    show noah_solace at center:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_solace "We can stage materials at my shop. Make a run tomorrow with the kids from the school. Teach 'em to plane a board right."

    mira_solace "We'll need volunteers to help with lifts and a couple of people who can handle the ledger."

    noah_solace "I can handle ledger if it means I get to keep hammering things."
    "Your voice meets theirs. The conversation expands—safety checks, tool rotations, who will watch the tide on workdays. People argue about finishing touches. The argument isn't ugly; it's the precise friction of care: someone wants sturdier bolts, another worries about affordability. You mediate without smoothing everything over, naming constraints and possibilities."
    "Arin Voss sidles close and shows you a quick sequence of photos: a child handing a sapling to an elder, a neighbor testing a prototype threshold, the way the light catches patched walkways and makes them glow. His images say what policy documents can't: this is already happening."
    hide etta_maren
    show arin_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "We should document the methods—short clips, nothing fancy. Teach others where the holes are."

    mira_solace "Teach the holes as much as the fixes. People need to know it's okay for something to fail once so they can learn."

    arin_voss "And they need to see themselves in the instructions. Not just you and me."
    "The workshop runs like a small machine: stations, someone sketching diagrams on a chalkboard, a line of people passing nails and stories along. You stand at the center of it and feel the current you set"
    "in motion pulse outward. Your notebook fills with measurements and names; your wristband records humidity and tide for later analysis. The tangible grows: a threshold bolted in place, a marsh plug planted in an experimental basin,"
    "laughter when a tarp refuses to cooperate."

    menu:
        "Lead the hands-on threshold demo":
            "You pick up a drill and guide a neighbor's hand. Your instructions are practical, calm, and specific; you hear the satisfaction in their breath when the bolt seats solidly. Teaching feels like building twice as much as doing."
        "Hold a small sit-down to document community concerns":
            "You gather five neighbors under a tarp and ask open questions: what scares you, what would you change? Their answers spill out—memories of loss, hopes for stability, practical notes about where kids play. You record it carefully, each voice another vector for the pilot's design."

    # --- merge ---
    "By late afternoon, the pier is a stitched map of small victories. The marsh plugs haven't stabilized the channel yet, but the berm lines show promise; the raised thresholds slow trickles that used to flood doorways."
    "Each small fix reframes the problem: mitigation isn't only walls and contracts, it's rearranging how people live with water."
    "Samir appears in the doorway of the workshop, carrying a waterproof tablet, sleeves flecked with data patches. He has the careful calm of someone who handles messy numbers and finds comfort in tidy charts."
    hide mira_solace
    show samir_hale at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "The initial readings look consistent with what you predicted. The soil porosity in the pilot beds is good—enough to absorb and release at the right rates. If we scale this to a block, we can model expected load reduction across tides."
    hide noah_solace
    show mira_solace at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "Model it for me. If we show numbers that match lived experience, we have something fundable."

    samir_hale "Numbers need stories to live. Bring me the stories; I'll give them the math."
    "His hesitance is a kind of tenderness—you see him weigh civic prudence against the urgency in your eyes. Arin Voss bumps your shoulder and grins as if the two of you are conspiring; his presence steadies the next steps."

    arin_voss "I can stitch the footage into short reels. People watch five minutes, not fifty."

    mira_solace "And we time it with tides, Samir. Match the clips to the data so it's not just words on a board."
    "The day folds into a warm orange. Children pedal through puddles they've been taught not to fear, learning instead where the water collects and where it drains. You note down community champions—the ones who step forward"
    "when a board needs carrying without being asked. You feel the movement of a network forming, each tie weaker than steel but stronger for being chosen."
    # [Scene: Tidehouse (Harborfront Research Lab) | Evening]
    hide arin_voss
    hide samir_hale
    hide mira_solace

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low hum of lab equipment, the distant ebb of the harbor; a kettle whistles gently]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle strings swelling into a steady, hopeful pulse]
    "Back at the Tidehouse, the light is warm and the air dense with the smell of tea and paper. You set your wet boots on the mat and unroll the day's notes. The lab feels like a home that was built around a problem set—functional, intimate, stubbornly optimistic."
    "Samir spreads out graphs while you pour tea. The lines on his tablet are tidy, the colors chosen to be legible at a distance."
    show samir_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "If we replicate the rooftop beds and pier thresholds across three more blocks, the model predicts a thirty percent reduction in emergency repair calls during moderate floods. That's a number the municipal office understands."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "Thirty percent sounds like breathing room. Enough to protect livelihoods if we sustain it."

    samir_hale "Sustainability is the condition. Maintenance schedules, community stewards, a small fund for parts—those are the thin things that make large things work."
    "You think of Noah's shop, of Etta's steady hands, of the way Arin took pictures as if each frame were a promise. The pilots are no longer solitary experiments; they are hinge points. Your mind catalogs"
    "next steps: volunteer training, an equipment schedule, a small emergency fund seeded by bake sales and donations."
    "Arin Voss arrives unannounced, camera in hand and a satchel of rough prints. He drops a photo on the table—a child pressing a hand to a newly raised threshold, eyes wide with the private triumph of being part of a fix."
    show arin_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "This could be the opening for the reels. People see that and they want in."

    mira_solace "They see themselves. That's the difference."

    arin_voss "We should make the reels honest—show the mess and the learning. Not just the neat finish."
    hide samir_hale
    show etta_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_maren "Keep the training small. Teach people to teach. After that, a pocket of good practice grows like a root system."

    mira_solace "We'll set up mentor pairs. One experienced neighbor, one newcomer."

    etta_maren "Yes. The old teach the new, and the new bring energy."
    "You feel the current of approvals and small agreements pulling the plan toward reality. The labs and reels and handbooks are scaffolding around a simpler fact: people want to protect where they belong, and they will if they can see exactly how."
    hide mira_solace
    show samir_hale at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "I'll run a six-week schedule for data collection. If we can show consistent reductions in load on municipal infrastructure, we can argue for small budget reallocations in the next fiscal."
    hide arin_voss
    show mira_solace at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "Six weeks for initial data, two months for community training, a pilot replication after the next spring tide. That becomes a year of demonstrable practice."

    samir_hale "It could work. And if the numbers line up, we can open a conversation with some sympathetic council members."
    hide etta_maren
    show arin_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "And I will make sure the reels are impossible to ignore."

    mira_solace "And we'll teach others how to make them."
    "You sit for a moment with your hands around the cup, feeling the heat against your palms. There's a map of modest deadlines in your head now, a lattice of tasks that feels both heavy and"
    "buoyant. The pilots are a test of technique, but also of willingness—willingness to invest time, to accept messy first tries, to show up when the tide turns."
    "You reach for your notebook and write three words large across a page: Teach. Repeat. Share. The phrase is almost a chant. It condenses the work into a procedural ethic you can hand to others."

    "Arin Voss leans forward, voice low" "You ever think—what if this catches? Not just here, but beyond? If Etta's method spreads, if Samir's numbers persuade, if Noah's shop trains a dozen more hands—"

    mira_solace "Then it's not just one neighborhood anymore. It's a pattern."
    "You feel a lift—a gentle, steady ascent, not euphoric but sure. The day's tiny victories stack; you can see a plausible line from seed to scale. The thought is dangerous in its hopefulness: what if? But it's a useful danger."
    "You stand and cross the lab to the window. The harbor reflects a dozen small lights—homes, lanterns, the rooftop lamps blinking like distant stars. You imagine each one as a node in a growing network where skills and care travel by hand."
    # [Page-Turn Moment]
    "You tuck your notebook into your jacket, feeling its bulk like a bundle of future plans, and step to the doorway. Outside, the tide moves with the same old patience. Inside, the people you trust move"
    "with new purpose. For tonight, that alignment holds. Tomorrow you'll begin the slow work of scaling: formalizing training, documenting failures, and making a case the city can't ignore."
    hide samir_hale
    hide mira_solace
    hide arin_voss

